  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Where can Typhoons happen and how are they formed?",
  "response": "Typhoons are tropical cyclones that occur in the northwest Pacific Ocean, particularly in regions near and to the south of Japan, as well as parts of Southeast Asia. They are similar to hurricanes (which occur in the Atlantic and northeastern Pacific) and cyclones (which occur in the South Pacific and Indian Ocean) but are specifically referred to as \u201ctyphoons\u201d in this part of the world.\n\n### Formation of Typhoons:\n\nTyphoons form under specific conditions, typically in the following manner:\n\n1. **Warm Ocean Waters**: Typhoons usually form over warm ocean waters, typically when sea surface temperatures are at least 26.5 degrees Celsius (about 80 degrees Fahrenheit) or higher. This warmth provides the energy necessary for the storm.\n\n2. **Atmospheric Instability**: The atmosphere needs to be unstable, which encourages rising air. The rising air helps to create a low-pressure center.\n\n3. **High Humidity**: High levels of moisture in the mid-levels of the atmosphere are important for typhoon development. This moisture helps fuel the storm, leading to the release of latent heat when water vapor condenses into cloud droplets.\n\n4. **Low Wind Shear**: Low vertical wind shear (the change in speed and direction of wind with height) is important for maintaining the organization of the storm. High wind shear can disrupt the formation and development of tropical cyclones.\n\n5. **Coriolis Effect**: The rotation of the Earth (Coriolis effect) is necessary for the cyclone to develop a rotating structure. This is why typhoons typically form away from the equator, where the Coriolis effect is too weak.\n\n### Stages of Development:\n\nTyphoons usually evolve through several stages:\n\n- **Tropical Disturbance**: An area of organized convection (thunderstorms) that has some potential for tropical cyclogenesis.\n\n- **Tropical Depression**: When a system has defined circulation and speeds of sustained winds are less than 39 mph (63 km/h).\n\n- **Tropical Storm**: When the sustained wind speeds reach between 39 mph and 74 mph (63 to 119 km/h).\n\n- **Typhoon**: Once sustained wind speeds reach 74 mph (119 km/h) or higher, the system is classified as a typhoon.\n\nTyphoons can be very destructive, causing flooding, landslides, and damage to infrastructure, making their formation and behavior a critical focus for meteorologists and disaster management officials.",
